## Repository Rules

```text
config/              project settings, URLs, ASGI/WSGI, environment wiring
apps/api/            DRF serializers, viewsets, routers, permissions
apps/users/          user and auth-related domain code
apps/common/         shared services and utilities
tests/integration/   API + database integration coverage
```

## Non-Negotiable Boundaries

1. Keep Django project config separate from domain apps.
2. Keep serializers focused on transport and validation, not orchestration-heavy business logic.
3. Keep permissions explicit and reusable; do not duplicate authorization rules across viewsets.
4. Put domain workflows into services or use-case modules, not into model methods by default.
5. Use migrations intentionally; schema drift is a real change, not background noise.

## DRF Conventions

- one router registration per resource group
- explicit serializers for create/update/read shapes where needed
- use viewsets only when they reduce noise without hiding behavior
- prefer explicit permission classes over ad-hoc inline checks
{% if use_drf_spectacular %}
- keep the OpenAPI output accurate through serializers, views, and schema annotations
{% endif %}

## Authentication Rules

{% if auth_strategy == "none" %}
- No auth is scaffolded. Treat any later auth addition as an architectural change.
{% elif auth_strategy == "session" %}
- Session auth fits browser-oriented internal systems. Keep CSRF and session boundaries explicit.
{% elif auth_strategy == "jwt" %}
- JWT auth belongs in dedicated auth modules and DRF authentication classes.
{% elif auth_strategy == "token" %}
- Token auth should be centralized and revocation semantics documented.
{% else %}
- OAuth2 provider integration belongs in infrastructure/auth modules, not inside business resources.
{% endif %}

## Testing Rules

{% if test_strategy == "pytest-django" %}
- prioritize pytest-django coverage for serializers, permissions, and service modules
- add smoke tests for the API surface
{% elif test_strategy == "pytest-django-and-integration" %}
- every exposed resource gets integration coverage for auth, validation, and persistence
- business workflow modules get focused unit tests
{% else %}
- maintain unit, integration, and broader workflow verification separately
{% endif %}

## Implementation Heuristics

- implement one app/resource at a time
- decide early whether logic belongs in serializer, service, permission, or model
- document structural exceptions in `docs/adrs/`
